SUMMARY:Journal of World Literature Event: Panel discussion on the Role of 
 Empathy in Literature
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Writing Associates Program']\\nCategory: Lectur
 e/Panel Discussion\\nJoin Susan Muaddi Darraj\, Arnab Dutta Roy\, and Shai
 len Mishra for a discussion on how narrative empathy can serve as a concep
 tual framework for thinking ethically about otherness and for Global South
  solidarities against colonialism and genocide. The event will also includ
 e a talk and reading by Prof. Muaddi Darraj\, and promotion of the upcomin
 g book Constructing the Other: Narrative Empathy and the Ethics of Border
 -Crossing in World Literature by Profs. Dutta Roy and Mishra.     Atten
 dees can join the event virtually as well. Please follow the link to regis
 ter: (link)   Susan Muaddi Darraj is the author of the novel Behind Yo
 u Is The Sea\, which received praise from The New York Times\, The San Fr
 ancisco Chronicle\, and Ms Magazine\; it was also named a Best Book of 
 2024 by The New Yorker. Her other major works are the short story collect
 ion\, A Curious Land\, and the Farah Rocks children’s book series. S
 he teaches creative writing at The Johns Hopkins University in Baltimore. 
 Arnab Dutta Roy is Assistant Professor of English at Florida Gulf Coast U
 niversity. His research is located at the intersection of postcolonialism\
 , human rights\, and modern South Asian literature. He has co-edited two b
 ooks on the postcolonial bildungsroman and a special issue on narrative em
 pathy and world literature in the Journal of World Literature.Shailen Mis
 hra is a Visiting Assistant Professor at Swarthmore College. His research
  interests include writing studies\, creative writing aesthetics\, and nar
 rative empathy. He has co-edited a special issue for the Journal of World
  Literature and his creative writing has appeared in DIAGRAM\, The Balt
 imore Review\, The Bookends Review\, and elsewhere.    This scholarly p
 romotion event is co-sponsored by the Aydelotte Foundation\, Swarthmore Co
 llege Libraries\, and the Department of Peace and Conflict Studies.   Th
 is event is free and to the public and the Tri-Co community.Accessibility 
 Information for the Intercultural Center (link) \\nDetails: https://swatc
 entral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D1390294610
LOCATION:Hormel/Nguyen Intercultural Center at Sproul Hall Room 201 Dome Ro
 om
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1390294610
CATEGORIES:Lecture/Panel Discussion
END:VEVENT
