SUMMARY:Narrating the Goddess: Professor Jessica Birkenholtz's Translation 
 on Swasthani Vrata Kartha
DESCRIPTION:Organized by: ['Interfaith Center']\\nCategory: Student Activit
 y (no alcohol)\\nThe Swasthani Vrata Katha is Nepal’s most widely read
  and recited Hindu devotional text. Dating to the late 16th century\, man
 y Nepali Hindus annually perform a month-long recitation of it still today
 . It is a collection of widely circulating Hindu myths about gods\, demons
 \, and divine dalliances that forefront the great god Shiva and the goddes
 ses Sati and Parvati. It is also a local folk story about women’s real\,
  everyday hardships and the rewards of attending to one’s dharma and dev
 otion to the goddess Swasthani. In this talk\, Professor Birkenholtz draw
 s on her decades-long study of the Swasthani to reflect\, first\, on how
  the Swasthani both prescribes idealized womanhood for Nepali women and 
 illustrates many lived realities. Second\, she will consider how the portr
 ayal and treatment of women is variously experienced as misogynistic or em
 powering among Nepali women. Finally\, Professor Birkenholtz will share he
 r experience as a feminist scholar of religion of translating the Swastha
 ni into English with a female Nepali scholar and collaborator.\\nDetails:
  https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D
 1385688771
LOCATION:McCabe LibLab\, Full Space\, Conference Room
URL:https://swatcentral.swarthmore.edu/?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%
 3D1385688771
CATEGORIES:Student Activity (no alcohol)
END:VEVENT
